# Sphinx Documentation - Guidelines

## Purpose
- Keep docs consistent, buildable, and easy to navigate.
- Avoid drifting docs: every change that affects behavior should update docs.

## Location and Structure
- Place docs under `docs/`.
- Keep a clear entry point (`index.rst` or `index.md`).
- Organize by topic: getting-started, configuration, operations, API usage, troubleshooting.
- Add new pages to a toctree so they appear in nav.

## Style and Formatting
- Prefer reStructuredText (`.rst`); if using MyST/Markdown, keep consistent per section.
- Use meaningful headings; one H1 per page.
- Use `.. code-block:: <lang>` with a language hint (e.g., `bash`, `python`, `toml`).
- Use admonitions for important notes: `.. note::`, `.. warning::`, `.. tip::`.
- Avoid hard-coding versions; reference `apps.core.version.__version__` in examples if shown.

## Cross-References
- Use Sphinx roles for internal links: ``:ref:`target` ``.
- Link to settings with clear paths (e.g., `config/settings/settings.toml`).
- Prefer relative links within `docs/`; avoid raw GitHub URLs unless necessary.

## API and Configuration Docs
- When adding/altering behaviors:
  - Update related sections in configuration docs.
  - Document new settings (name, type, default, required/optional).
  - Note backward-compatibility and migration steps if relevant.
- Keep examples minimal but runnable; avoid fictional secrets/PII.

## Builds and Validation
- Ensure `make html` (or the project’s doc build command) succeeds before merge.
- Fix warnings; don’t ignore broken refs or missing toctree entries.

## Writing Pitfalls to Avoid
- No secrets/tokens in snippets.
- Don’t duplicate content across pages; link or ref instead.
- Keep line length reasonable; wrap long paragraphs.
- Don’t paste large logs; summarize and link to runbooks if needed.

## Checklist Before Merging Doc Changes
- Added to toctree/nav.
- Code blocks have language specified.
- No secrets/PII in text or examples.
- Build succeeds without warnings.
